        {
          "type": "heading",
          "value": "Introduction to Package Management"
        },
        {
          "type": "definition",
          "value": "Package management is the process of installing, updating, and removing software on Linux using built-in tools called package managers."
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "value": "Different Linux distributions use different package managers. Debian and Ubuntu use apt, while RedHat and CentOS use yum or dnf. These tools help install software safely with all necessary dependencies."
        },
        {
          "type": "table",
          "value": [
            ["Distribution", "Package Manager"],
            ["Ubuntu / Debian", "apt / dpkg"],
            ["CentOS / RHEL", "yum / dnf"],
            ["Arch Linux", "pacman"],
            ["SUSE / OpenSUSE", "zypper"]
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "tip",
          "value": "Always update package lists before installing new software to avoid errors."
        }
      ],
      "video": {
        "platform": "youtube",
        "url": "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lkii2cGuKao"
      }
    },


    {
      "slideId": 2,
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "value": "Managing Packages on Ubuntu/Debian (APT)"
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "value": "APT is the most common package manager for beginner-friendly Linux distributions."
        },
        {
          "type": "code",
          "command": "sudo apt update",
          "description": "Refreshes package list (check for new versions). Run this first!"
        },
        {
          "type": "code",
          "command": "sudo apt install packageName",
          "description": "Installs a new software package."
        },
        {
          "type": "code",
          "command": "sudo apt remove packageName",
          "description": "Removes an installed package but keeps configuration files."
        },
        {
          "type": "code",
          "command": "sudo apt purge packageName",
          "description": "Completely removes package & configuration files."
        },
        {
          "type": "code",
          "command": "sudo apt upgrade",
          "description": "Updates all installed packages to latest versions."
        },
        {
          "type": "tip",
          "value": "Use apt update before apt upgrade to get the newest package info."
        }
      ],
      "video": null
    },


    {
      "slideId": 3,
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "value": "Managing Packages on RHEL/CentOS (YUM/DNF)"
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "value": "YUM and DNF are package managers used on RedHat-based systems like CentOS, Fedora, and RHEL."
        },
        {
          "type": "code",
          "command": "sudo dnf install packageName",
          "description": "Install software (DNF is the modern version of YUM)."
        },
        {
          "type": "code",
          "command": "sudo dnf remove packageName",
          "description": "Remove an installed package."
        },
        {
          "type": "code",
          "command": "sudo dnf update",
          "description": "Update all packages to the newest version."
        },
        {
          "type": "tip",
          "value": "On older systems, yum is used instead of dnf."
        }
      ],
      "video": null
    },


    {
      "slideId": 4,
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "value": "Low-Level Package Tools (dpkg & rpm)"
        },
        {
          "type": "text",
          "value": "These tools install local package files when you donâ€™t use online repositories."
        },
        {
          "type": "code",
          "command": "sudo dpkg -i package.deb",
          "description": "Install a .deb file (Debian/Ubuntu)."
        },
        {
          "type": "code",
          "command": "sudo rpm -ivh package.rpm",
          "description": "Install an .rpm file (RedHat/CentOS)."
        },
        {
          "type": "tip",
          "value": "If dpkg shows dependency errors, fix them with: sudo apt --fix-broken install"
        }
      ],
      "video": null
    },


